</p>

<p class="section">The implementation has been carried out as follows:</p>

<ul>

<li>
<b>Two generic views have been created</b>, as requested:
<ul>
<li>One view for <b>Position Breaks (ls_type = 9030, 9099)</b>.</li>
<li>One view for <b>Break Details (ls_type &lt;&gt; 9030, 9099)</b>.</li>
</ul>

These views are responsible only for retrieving the required data from the underlying tables and do not contain any report-specific business logic.
</li>

<li>
<b>Business logic has been moved out of the views</b> and implemented in the
<b>BIRT report dataset SELECT query</b>, in line with your recommendation.
</li>

<li>
<b>Formatting logic</b> (date formats, number formats, etc.) has been removed
from both the SQL views and the dataset queries. The formatting is now handled
at the <b>BIRT cell/column level</b>.
</li>

</ul>

<p class="section">Aggregation Logic</p>

<p>
Regarding the aggregation logic, we evaluated different implementation
approaches. Since the aggregation calculations are tightly coupled with the
corresponding business rules, separating them completely from the aggregation
logic would significantly complicate the implementation and reduce
maintainability.
</p>

<p>
Based on our earlier discussion and agreement, we have therefore implemented
the aggregation portion using a <b>single reusable CTE</b>. This CTE performs
the common aggregation logic required for the different SourceDB values
(<b>Daily, Monthly, Hedge, NSCC</b>, etc.) and contains only the business logic
that is inherently required for those aggregation calculations. The report
dataset then uses this common CTE together with a single SELECT statement to
retrieve the final output.
</p>

<p class="section">With this approach:</p>

<ul>
<li>The views remain <b>generic and reusable</b>.</li>

<li>Report-specific business logic remains <b>outside the views</b>.</li>

<li>Formatting is handled entirely within <b>BIRT</b>.</li>

<li>
Common aggregation logic is centralized in a
<b>single reusable CTE</b>, minimizing duplication while keeping the
implementation maintainable.
</li>
</ul>

<p>
The first two reports have now been completed using this approach and are
<b>ready for your review</b>.
